{{short description|The sea between Bear Island in the south of Svalbard and the north of Norway through which water flows from the Atlantic into the Arctic Ocean}}
[[File:Golfstream.jpg|thumb|The upper right arrow symbolizes the [[Norwegian Current]] flowing through the '''BSO'''. Some waters originates from
the [[North Atlantic Current]] which continues the [[Gulf Stream]] to the North-East.]]
The '''Barents Sea Opening (BSO)''' is an [[oceanographic]] term for the Western [[Barents Sea]], the sea area between [[Bear Island (Norway)|Bear Island]] in the south of [[Svalbard]] and the northern extremity of [[Norway]] through which a [[water mass]] of [[Atlantic]] origin flows into the [[Arctic Ocean]].<ref name=AtlanticHeat>{{cite journal|last=Årthun|first=M.|author2=Eldevik, T.|author3= Smedsrud, L. H.|author4= Skagseth, Ø.|author5= Ingvaldsen, R. B.|title=Quantifying the Influence of Atlantic Heat on Barents Sea Ice Variability and Retreat*|journal=Journal of Climate|date=1 July 2012|volume=25|issue=13|pages=4736–4743|doi=10.1175/JCLI-D-11-00466.1}}</ref> The inflow of relative warm water into the [[Arctic Ocean]] occurs not only through the Barents Sea Opening, but also through [[Fram Strait]] which is much deeper. The [[internal energy]] entering the colder waters has an influence on the [[atmosphere]] and the [[sea ice]] above and therefore possibly on the global [[climate]].

==Oceanographic measurements==
The [[Norwegian Polar Institute]] performs about six
[[hydrography|hydrographic]] survey per year across the Barents Sea Opening from {{coord|71.58|N|20|E}} to {{coord|73.58|N|20|E}} since 1977.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ingvaldsen|first=Randi B.|title=Velocity field of the western entrance to the Barents Sea|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research|date=1 January 2004|volume=109|issue=C3|doi=10.1029/2003JC001811}}</ref> 
A set of [[Current meter|oceanographic current meters]] captures the seasonal cycle of the inflow since 1997. Roughly every 30 [[Nautical mile|nm]] two instruments are deployed, one at 50 [[m]] depth, and another 15 [[m]] above the [[sea floor]].

