'''Mashu''', as described in the [[Epic of Gilgamesh]] of [[Mesopotamian mythology]], is a great [[Cedrus libani|cedar]] [[mountain]] through which the hero-king [[Gilgamesh]] passes via a tunnel on his journey to [[Dilmun]] after leaving the [[Cedar Forest]], a forest of ten thousand leagues span.<ref name="UnwinUnwin1996">{{cite book|author1=P. T. H. Unwin|author2=Tim Unwin|title=Wine and the Vine: An Historical Geography of Viticulture and the Wine Trade|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U6XRp6gY8ucC&pg=PA80|accessdate=31 May 2011|date=18 June 1996|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-14416-2|pages=80–}}</ref> [[Siduri]], the Alewife, lived on the shore, associated with "the Waters of Death" that Gilgamesh had to cross to reach [[Utnapishtim]], the far-away.{{Clarify|reason=incomplete sentence|date=October 2015}}<ref>Trample, Christopher "A Maiden Guards the Door: Symbolism and Meaning in Mythology" (http://www.public.iastate.edu/~ctrampel/Trampel_Mythology_Journal_Format2.pdf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}), accessed 02.09.2013</ref>
==Possible real location reference for story== The corresponding location in reality has been the topic of speculation, as no confirming evidence has been found. [[Jeffrey H. Tigay]] suggests that in the Sumerian version, through its association with the sun god Utu, "(t)he Cedar Mountain is implicitly located in the east, whereas in the [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] versions, Gilgamesh's destination (is) removed from the east" and "explicitly located in the north west, in or near Lebanon".<ref name="Tigay2002">{{cite book|author=Jeffrey H. Tigay|authorlink=Jeffrey H. Tigay|title=The evolution of the Gilgamesh epic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cxjuHTH6I2sC&pg=PA78|accessdate=29 June 2011|date=November 2002|publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci Publishers|isbn=978-0-86516-546-5|pages=76-78}}</ref>
